1
00:00:09,343 --> 00:00:11,428
(HUMMING)

2
00:00:17,518 --> 00:00:19,853
-What do you want?
-The nurse sent me, sir.

3
00:00:19,937 --> 00:00:21,730
I was in English and I got a headache.

4
00:00:21,813 --> 00:00:24,274
-Then don't bother me, go home.
-I can't.

5
00:00:24,399 --> 00:00:26,902
Why? Is your mother at work?

6
00:00:26,985 --> 00:00:29,988
I live in Ambrose Hall, the children's home.

7
00:00:30,113 --> 00:00:32,991
No parents? No one to miss you?

8
00:00:33,075 --> 00:00:35,160
I see why the nurse sent you.

9
00:00:35,786 --> 00:00:37,287
You poor child.

10
00:00:37,412 --> 00:00:40,749
Poor, thin child.

11
00:00:41,458 --> 00:00:42,876
Come inside.

12
00:00:46,213 --> 00:00:48,465
It's nearly time for lunch.

13
00:00:51,176 --> 00:00:52,719
(SCREECHING)

14
00:00:52,803 --> 00:00:54,763
(GIRL SCREAMING)

15
00:00:54,846 --> 00:00:56,974
(SCHOOL BELL RINGING)

16
00:01:07,693 --> 00:01:09,820
Good morning, class.

17
00:01:09,945 --> 00:01:11,989
Are we sitting comfortably?

18
00:01:13,282 --> 00:01:16,076
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

19
00:01:50,861 --> 00:01:53,905
So...physics.

20
00:01:56,700 --> 00:02:00,704
Physics, eh? Physics.

21
00:02:00,829 --> 00:02:03,373
Physics.

22
00:02:03,457 --> 00:02:08,420
Physics! Physics. Physics. Physics.
Physics. Physics. Physics. Physics.

23
00:02:09,463 --> 00:02:12,716
I hope one of you is getting all this down.
Okay, let's see what you know.

24
00:02:12,799 --> 00:02:15,886
Two identical strips of nylon
are charged with static electricity

25
00:02:15,969 --> 00:02:17,888
and hung from a string
so they can swing freely.

26
00:02:18,013 --> 00:02:19,973
What would happen
if they were brought near each other?

27
00:02:20,057 --> 00:02:21,808
-Yes, what's your name?
-Milo.

28
00:02:21,892 --> 00:02:23,143
Milo. Off you go.

29
00:02:23,226 --> 00:02:25,562
They'd repel each other
because they have the same charge.

30
00:02:25,646 --> 00:02:27,064
Correct-amundo.

31
00:02:27,147 --> 00:02:30,525
A word I have never used before
and hopefully never will again.

32
00:02:30,609 --> 00:02:34,029
Question two.
I coil up a thin piece of nichrome wire

33
00:02:34,112 --> 00:02:36,948
and place it in a glass of water.

34
00:02:37,032 --> 00:02:38,408
Then I turn on the electricity

35
00:02:38,492 --> 00:02:40,410
and measure to see
if the water temperature is affected.

36
00:02:40,535 --> 00:02:44,748
My question is this. How do I measure
the electrical power going into the coil?

37
00:02:44,873 --> 00:02:46,667
Someone else.

38
00:02:48,710 --> 00:02:50,962
No? Okay. Milo, go for it.

39
00:02:51,046 --> 00:02:54,174
Measure the current and PD
using an ammeter and voltmeter.

40
00:02:54,257 --> 00:02:55,926
Two to Milo! Right, Milo, tell me this.

41
00:02:56,009 --> 00:02:57,761
True or false,
the greater the damping on a system,

42
00:02:57,886 --> 00:02:59,471
the quicker it loses energy
to its surroundings.

43
00:02:59,596 --> 00:03:01,181
-False.
-What is non-coding DNA?

44
00:03:01,306 --> 00:03:02,724
DNA that doesn't code for a protein.

45
00:03:02,808 --> 00:03:06,978
-65,983 times 5.
-329,915.

46
00:03:07,062 --> 00:03:08,689
How do you travel faster than light?

47
00:03:08,772 --> 00:03:12,234
By harnessing a quantum tunnel
with an FTL factor of 36.7 recurring.

48
00:03:39,761 --> 00:03:40,929
Two days.

49
00:03:41,012 --> 00:03:44,057
Sorry, could you just...
There's a bit of gravy.

50
00:03:44,141 --> 00:03:46,893
-No, no, just there.
-Two days we've been here.

51
00:03:46,977 --> 00:03:49,730
Blame your boyfriend.
He's the one who put us on to this.

52
00:03:49,813 --> 00:03:53,734
He was right. Boy in class this morning,
got knowledge way beyond planet Earth.

53
00:03:53,817 --> 00:03:57,195
-You eating those chips?
-Yeah, they're a bit...different.

54
00:03:57,320 --> 00:04:00,490
I think they're gorgeous.
Wish I had school dinners like this.

55
00:04:00,574 --> 00:04:02,367
It's very well behaved this place.

56
00:04:02,451 --> 00:04:03,994
I thought they'd all be
happy-slapping hoodies.

57
00:04:04,077 --> 00:04:05,620
Happy-slapping hoodies with ASBOs.

58
00:04:05,704 --> 00:04:09,249
Happy-slapping hoodies with ASBOs
and ringtones. Eh?

59
00:04:09,332 --> 00:04:11,376
Don't tell me I don't fit in.

60
00:04:11,460 --> 00:04:14,212
You are not permitted to leave your station
during a sitting.

61
00:04:14,337 --> 00:04:15,756
I was just talking to this teacher.

62
00:04:15,839 --> 00:04:18,216
-Hello.
-He doesn't like the chips.

63
00:04:18,341 --> 00:04:21,428
The menu has been specifically designed
by the headmaster

64
00:04:21,511 --> 00:04:24,181
to improve concentration and performance.

65
00:04:24,264 --> 00:04:26,183
Now get back to work.

66
00:04:26,892 --> 00:04:30,562
See? This is me. Dinner lady.

67
00:04:30,687 --> 00:04:34,107
-I'll have the crumble.
-I'm so gonna kill you.

68
00:04:37,235 --> 00:04:38,737
Melissa.

69
00:04:38,820 --> 00:04:41,364
You'll be joining my class
for the next period.

70
00:04:41,490 --> 00:04:44,910
Milo's failed me so it's time
we moved you up to the top class.

71
00:04:44,993 --> 00:04:47,329
-Kenny, not eating the chips?
-I'm not allowed.

72
00:04:47,412 --> 00:04:49,581
Luke, extra class. Now!

73
00:05:03,053 --> 00:05:08,058
WOMAN: Careful, keep it steady.
Don't spill a drop.

74
00:05:08,141 --> 00:05:11,728
I said keep it steady. Careful.

75
00:05:11,812 --> 00:05:15,065
That's it. Easy now. Steady.

76
00:05:15,148 --> 00:05:16,775
(MOBILE RINGING)

77
00:05:16,858 --> 00:05:18,735
Right, second barrel, quickly now.

78
00:05:18,819 --> 00:05:20,570
-What have you got?
-MICKEY: Confirmation.

79
00:05:20,654 --> 00:05:24,157
I just got into army records.
Three months ago, massive UFO activity.

80
00:05:24,241 --> 00:05:27,285
They logged over 40 sightings.
Lights in the sky, all of that.

81
00:05:27,369 --> 00:05:30,455
Can't get any photos
'cause then it gets all classified, secret.

82
00:05:30,539 --> 00:05:32,415
-Keeps locking me out.
-Tell you what, though.

83
00:05:32,499 --> 00:05:35,752
Three months ago, turns out
all the kitchen staff were replaced.

84
00:05:35,836 --> 00:05:37,337
And this lot are weird.

85
00:05:37,420 --> 00:05:40,257
There's definitely something going on.
I was right to call you home.

86
00:05:40,340 --> 00:05:44,094
I thought maybe you called me home just...
Well, just to call me home.

87
00:05:44,261 --> 00:05:46,054
Do you think I'd just invent an emergency?

88
00:05:46,137 --> 00:05:48,390
-You could've done.
-That's the last thing I'd do.

89
00:05:48,473 --> 00:05:51,226
'Cause every time I see you,
an emergency just gets in the way.

90
00:05:52,102 --> 00:05:54,312
(WOMAN SCREAMING)

91
00:05:54,396 --> 00:05:55,772
I've got to go.

92
00:05:56,481 --> 00:05:57,858
Get her up, get her up!

93
00:05:57,941 --> 00:06:00,193
Rose, what is it? What...

94
00:06:00,277 --> 00:06:01,778
(SCREAMING)

95
00:06:10,287 --> 00:06:12,372
-What you doing?
-Calling an ambulance.

96
00:06:12,455 --> 00:06:14,833
No need, she's quite all right.

97
00:06:16,251 --> 00:06:18,628
(SCREAMING)

98
00:06:18,712 --> 00:06:21,089
It's fine. She does that.

99
00:06:31,474 --> 00:06:34,978
I'd like you all to
put your headphones on now, please.

100
00:06:35,812 --> 00:06:38,940
Oh, children, the things you will see.

101
00:07:26,863 --> 00:07:28,573
Mathematics.
That's the cornerstone of our work here.

102
00:07:28,657 --> 00:07:32,118
But my improvements aren't confined
to the classroom. No, no, no.

103
00:07:32,202 --> 00:07:34,162
We've introduced a new policy here.

104
00:07:34,245 --> 00:07:38,375
School dinners are absolutely free,
but compulsory. Do try the chips.

105
00:07:38,458 --> 00:07:41,586
Oh, I'd love to, thank you.
And it's got to be said,

106
00:07:41,670 --> 00:07:44,089
the transformation you've brought about,
it's amazing.

107
00:07:44,172 --> 00:07:47,759
I mean, maybe you're working the children
a little bit too hard now and then,

108
00:07:47,884 --> 00:07:50,804
but I think good results
are more important than anything.

109
00:07:50,887 --> 00:07:53,431
Exactly. You're a woman of vision,
Miss Smith.

110
00:07:53,556 --> 00:07:56,977
Oh, I can see everything, Mr Finch.
Quite clearly.

111
00:07:57,060 --> 00:07:58,937
Yesterday I had a 12-year-old girl

112
00:07:59,020 --> 00:08:02,774
give me the exact height
of the walls of Troy in cubits.

113
00:08:02,857 --> 00:08:04,818
And it's ever since
the new headmaster arrived?

114
00:08:04,901 --> 00:08:09,072
Finch arrived three months ago,
next day half the staff got flu.

115
00:08:09,155 --> 00:08:11,241
Finch replaced them with that lot.

116
00:08:11,324 --> 00:08:14,869
Except for the teacher you replaced,
and that was just plain weird,

117
00:08:14,953 --> 00:08:16,705
her winning the lottery like that.

118
00:08:16,788 --> 00:08:18,498
-How's that weird?
-She never played.

119
00:08:18,581 --> 00:08:21,459
Said the ticket was posted
through her door at midnight.

120
00:08:21,543 --> 00:08:23,253
Hmm?

121
00:08:23,336 --> 00:08:25,046
The world is very strange.

122
00:08:25,130 --> 00:08:28,758
FINCH: Excuse me, colleagues.
A moment of your time.

123
00:08:29,718 --> 00:08:33,722
May I introduce Miss Sarah Jane Smith.
Miss Smith is a journalist

124
00:08:33,805 --> 00:08:37,350
who's writing a profile about me
for The Sunday Times.

125
00:08:37,434 --> 00:08:42,022
I thought it might be useful for her to get
a view from the trenches, so to speak.

126
00:08:42,105 --> 00:08:44,107
Don't spare my blushes.

127
00:08:45,984 --> 00:08:47,694
Hello.

128
00:08:47,861 --> 00:08:49,612
Oh, I should think so.

129
00:08:49,988 --> 00:08:51,656
And you are?

130
00:08:51,740 --> 00:08:54,534
Mmm? Uh, Smith. John Smith.

131
00:08:54,617 --> 00:08:56,036
John Smith?

132
00:08:57,162 --> 00:09:00,457
I used to have a friend
who sometimes went by that name.

133
00:09:00,540 --> 00:09:02,333
Well, it's a very common name.

134
00:09:02,417 --> 00:09:05,837
He was a very uncommon man.

135
00:09:06,546 --> 00:09:08,131
-Nice to meet you.
-Nice to meet you!

136
00:09:08,214 --> 00:09:11,301
Yes. Very nice. More than nice. Brilliant.

137
00:09:11,384 --> 00:09:15,638
So, have you worked here long?

138
00:09:16,014 --> 00:09:18,767
No, it's only my second day.

139
00:09:18,850 --> 00:09:22,896
Oh, you're new, then?
So what do you think of the school?

140
00:09:22,979 --> 00:09:24,689
I mean, this new curriculum,

141
00:09:24,814 --> 00:09:27,984
so many children getting ill.
Doesn't that strike you as odd?

142
00:09:28,068 --> 00:09:30,403
You don't sound like someone
just doing a profile.

143
00:09:30,487 --> 00:09:33,406
Well, no harm in a little investigation
while I'm here.

144
00:09:33,490 --> 00:09:36,493
No, good for you. Good for you.

145
00:09:37,035 --> 00:09:40,830
Oh, good for you, Sarah Jane Smith.

146
00:09:41,164 --> 00:09:42,999
(SCHOOL BELL RINGING)

147
00:10:04,729 --> 00:10:06,523
(GROWLING)

148
00:10:10,693 --> 00:10:12,112
(CRUNCHING)

149
00:10:21,996 --> 00:10:23,164
(SCREECHING)

150
00:10:27,752 --> 00:10:31,881
This isn't your classroom, Kenny.
Now run along.

151
00:10:58,658 --> 00:11:00,535
(DOGS BARKING)

152
00:11:04,164 --> 00:11:07,208
ROSE: Oh! It's weird seeing school at night.

153
00:11:07,292 --> 00:11:08,835
It just feels wrong.

154
00:11:10,712 --> 00:11:14,174
When I was a kid, I used to think
all the teachers slept in school.

155
00:11:14,257 --> 00:11:17,010
All right, team...
Oh, I hate people who say "team".

156
00:11:17,093 --> 00:11:19,262
Uh, gang.

157
00:11:19,387 --> 00:11:21,014
Erm...

158
00:11:21,097 --> 00:11:22,891
comrades.

159
00:11:22,974 --> 00:11:25,727
Anyway, Rose, go to the kitchen,
get a sample of that oil.

160
00:11:25,810 --> 00:11:28,646
Mickey, the new staff are all maths
teachers. Check out the maths department.

161
00:11:28,771 --> 00:11:32,525
I'm gonna look in Finch's office.
Meet back here in 10 minutes.

162
00:11:32,609 --> 00:11:34,235
You gonna be all right?

163
00:11:34,319 --> 00:11:36,446
(SCOFFING) Me? Please.

164
00:11:36,529 --> 00:11:40,033
Infiltration and investigation?
I'm an expert at this.

165
00:11:47,832 --> 00:11:49,584
Where's the maths department?

166
00:11:49,667 --> 00:11:52,670
Down there, turn left,
through the fire doors, on the right.

167
00:11:52,795 --> 00:11:54,464
Thank you.

168
00:11:57,800 --> 00:11:59,844
(SCREECHING)

169
00:12:13,274 --> 00:12:15,318
(THUDDING)

170
00:12:26,412 --> 00:12:28,289
(SCREECHING)

171
00:12:57,026 --> 00:12:58,569
Hello, Sarah Jane.

172
00:12:58,945 --> 00:13:00,196
It's you.

173
00:13:02,156 --> 00:13:03,449
Doctor.

174
00:13:03,533 --> 00:13:05,952
Oh, my God. It's you, isn't it?

175
00:13:08,162 --> 00:13:10,164
-You've regenerated.
-Yeah.

176
00:13:10,248 --> 00:13:13,084
Half a dozen times since we last met.

177
00:13:13,209 --> 00:13:15,545
You look...

178
00:13:16,921 --> 00:13:18,214
incredible.

179
00:13:18,298 --> 00:13:19,966
So do you.

180
00:13:21,551 --> 00:13:23,011
I got old.

181
00:13:26,389 --> 00:13:27,765
What are you doing here?

182
00:13:27,890 --> 00:13:32,562
Well, UFO sighting,
school gets record results. I couldn't resist.

183
00:13:32,687 --> 00:13:35,690
-What about you?
-The same.

184
00:13:37,942 --> 00:13:39,193
I thought you'd died.

185
00:13:39,277 --> 00:13:42,697
I waited for you, you didn't come back
and I thought you must have died.

186
00:13:42,780 --> 00:13:46,034
I lived. Everyone else died.

187
00:13:46,909 --> 00:13:49,746
-What do you mean?
-Everyone died, Sarah.

188
00:13:51,664 --> 00:13:54,083
I can't believe it's you.

189
00:13:54,208 --> 00:13:55,877
(PIERCING SCREAM)

190
00:13:55,960 --> 00:13:58,254
Okay, now I can.

191
00:14:01,007 --> 00:14:02,842
Did you hear that?

192
00:14:02,925 --> 00:14:05,970
-Who's she?
-Rose, Sarah Jane. Sarah Jane, Rose.

193
00:14:06,596 --> 00:14:08,723
Hi. Nice to meet you.

194
00:14:08,806 --> 00:14:11,517
You can tell you're getting older,
your assistants are getting younger.

195
00:14:11,601 --> 00:14:14,103
-I'm not his assistant.
-No?

196
00:14:14,228 --> 00:14:15,605
Get you, tiger.

197
00:14:19,567 --> 00:14:21,903
Sorry. Sorry, it was only me.

198
00:14:21,986 --> 00:14:24,906
You told me to investigate so I started
looking through these cupboards

199
00:14:24,989 --> 00:14:27,784
-and all these fell out on me.
-Oh, my God, they're rats.

200
00:14:27,867 --> 00:14:31,871
Dozens of rats. Vacuum-packed rats!

201
00:14:31,954 --> 00:14:34,290
-And you decided to scream?
-It took me by surprise.

202
00:14:34,374 --> 00:14:36,501
-Like a little girl.
-It was dark! I was covered in rats!

203
00:14:36,584 --> 00:14:38,920
Nine, maybe ten years old.
I'm seeing pigtails, frilly skirt.

204
00:14:39,003 --> 00:14:40,463
ROSE: Hello, can we focus?

205
00:14:40,546 --> 00:14:42,799
Has anyone noticed
anything strange about this?

206
00:14:42,882 --> 00:14:44,300
Rats in school?

207
00:14:44,384 --> 00:14:47,804
Well, obviously, they use them
in biology lessons, they dissect them.

208
00:14:47,887 --> 00:14:50,556
Or maybe you haven't reached that bit yet.
How old are you?

209
00:14:50,640 --> 00:14:53,059
Excuse me,
no one dissects rats in school anymore.

210
00:14:53,142 --> 00:14:56,312
They haven't done that for years.
Where are you from, the Dark Ages?

211
00:14:56,396 --> 00:14:57,772
Anyway! Moving on...

212
00:14:57,855 --> 00:15:02,110
Everything started when Mr Finch arrived.
We should go and check his office.

213
00:15:02,902 --> 00:15:06,239
I don't mean to be rude or anything,
but who exactly are you?

214
00:15:06,322 --> 00:15:09,867
Sarah Jane Smith.
I used to travel with the Doctor.

215
00:15:09,951 --> 00:15:12,078
Oh! Well, he's never mentioned you.

216
00:15:12,161 --> 00:15:14,831
Oh, I must've done. Sarah Jane.
I mention her all the time.

217
00:15:14,914 --> 00:15:18,501
Hold on, sorry...never.

218
00:15:18,584 --> 00:15:22,839
What, not even once?
He didn't mention me even once?

219
00:15:22,922 --> 00:15:27,343
Oh, mate. The missus and the ex.
Welcome to every man's worst nightmare.

220
00:15:27,927 --> 00:15:30,847
DOCTOR: Maybe those rats were food.
ROSE: Food for what?

221
00:15:35,560 --> 00:15:37,186
Rose.

222
00:15:37,270 --> 00:15:41,274
You know how you used to think
all the teachers slept in the school?

223
00:15:41,858 --> 00:15:45,194
Well, they do.

224
00:15:49,699 --> 00:15:51,617
MICKEY: No way!

225
00:15:57,957 --> 00:15:59,292
(SCREECHES)

226
00:16:02,879 --> 00:16:06,924
-I am not going back in there. No way!
-Those were the teachers?

227
00:16:07,008 --> 00:16:08,801
When Finch arrived,
he brought with him seven new teachers,

228
00:16:08,885 --> 00:16:12,430
four dinner ladies and a nurse, 13.
Thirteen big bat people. Come on.

229
00:16:12,513 --> 00:16:14,557
-You've got to be kidding.
-I need the Tardis.

230
00:16:14,724 --> 00:16:16,434
I've got to analyse that oil
from the kitchen.

231
00:16:16,559 --> 00:16:19,604
I might be able to help you there.
I've got something to show you.

232
00:16:24,275 --> 00:16:25,818
KO!

233
00:16:25,902 --> 00:16:29,989
Rose Tyler, Mickey Smith,
allow me to introduce K9.

234
00:16:30,072 --> 00:16:32,241
Well, K9 Mark 3 to be precise.

235
00:16:32,325 --> 00:16:34,660
Why does he look so...disco?

236
00:16:34,744 --> 00:16:38,080
Oi! Listen, in the year 5,000
this was cutting edge.

237
00:16:38,164 --> 00:16:41,501
-What's happened to him?
-One day, just... Nothing.

238
00:16:41,584 --> 00:16:43,628
Didn't you try and get him repaired?

239
00:16:43,711 --> 00:16:45,546
It's not like getting parts for a Mini Metro.

240
00:16:45,630 --> 00:16:48,466
Besides, the technology inside him
could rewrite human science.

241
00:16:48,549 --> 00:16:50,301
I couldn't show him to anyone.

242
00:16:50,384 --> 00:16:54,096
Ooh, what's the nasty lady done to you, eh?

243
00:16:58,518 --> 00:17:02,063
ROSE: Look, no offence, but can you two
just stop petting for a minute?

244
00:17:02,146 --> 00:17:04,732
Never mind the tin dog, we're busy.

245
00:17:06,400 --> 00:17:08,986
(SCREECHING)

246
00:17:15,159 --> 00:17:18,412
You see, what's impressive is that
it's been nearly an hour since we met her

247
00:17:18,496 --> 00:17:21,123
-and I still haven't said "I told you so".
-I'm not listening to this.

248
00:17:21,207 --> 00:17:23,417
Though I have prepared
a little "I was right" dance

249
00:17:23,501 --> 00:17:25,086
that I can show you later.

250
00:17:25,169 --> 00:17:26,879
Two quid, love.

251
00:17:28,839 --> 00:17:31,676
All this time you've been giving it
"he's different”,

252
00:17:31,759 --> 00:17:34,387
but the truth is,
he's just like any other bloke.

253
00:17:34,470 --> 00:17:37,807
-You don't know what you're talking about.
-Maybe not.

254
00:17:38,975 --> 00:17:42,478
But if I were you, I'd go easy on the chips.

255
00:17:47,650 --> 00:17:49,610
FINCH: Come to me.

256
00:17:50,486 --> 00:17:52,280
Come to me.

257
00:18:05,084 --> 00:18:08,629
I thought of you on Christmas Day,
this Christmas just gone.

258
00:18:08,713 --> 00:18:12,133
Great big spaceship overhead, I thought,
"Oh, yeah! Bet he's up there."

259
00:18:12,216 --> 00:18:13,884
Right on top of it, yeah.

260
00:18:13,968 --> 00:18:16,095
-And Rose?
-She was there, too.

261
00:18:20,182 --> 00:18:22,560
Did I do something wrong?
'Cause you never came back for me.

262
00:18:22,685 --> 00:18:24,312
You just dumped me.

263
00:18:24,395 --> 00:18:27,690
I told you, I was called back home
and in those days humans weren't allowed.

264
00:18:27,773 --> 00:18:29,233
I waited for you.

265
00:18:30,359 --> 00:18:32,862
-I missed you.
-Oh, you didn't need me.

266
00:18:32,987 --> 00:18:35,865
-You were getting on with your life.
-You were my life.

267
00:18:38,242 --> 00:18:40,911
You know what
the most difficult thing was?

268
00:18:40,995 --> 00:18:44,498
Coping with what happens next.
You know, with what doesn't happen next.

269
00:18:44,582 --> 00:18:47,043
You took me
to the furthest reaches of the galaxy,

270
00:18:47,126 --> 00:18:49,962
you showed me supernovas,
intergalactic battles,

271
00:18:50,046 --> 00:18:53,007
and then you just dropped me
back on Earth.

272
00:18:53,090 --> 00:18:55,343
How could anything compare to that?

273
00:18:55,426 --> 00:18:57,845
All those things you saw,
you want me to apologise for that?

274
00:18:57,928 --> 00:19:03,726
No, but...we get a taste of that splendour
and then we have to go back.

275
00:19:03,809 --> 00:19:06,020
But look at you, you're investigating.

276
00:19:06,103 --> 00:19:08,606
You found that school.
You're doing what we always did.

277
00:19:08,689 --> 00:19:10,399
You could have come back.

278
00:19:12,026 --> 00:19:14,153
-I couldn't.
-Why not?

279
00:19:21,744 --> 00:19:23,079
It wasn't Croydon.

280
00:19:23,162 --> 00:19:24,914
Where you dropped me off,
it wasn't Croydon.

281
00:19:24,997 --> 00:19:26,874
-Where was it?
-Aberdeen.

282
00:19:28,584 --> 00:19:32,171
Right. That's next to Croydon, isn't it?

283
00:19:32,254 --> 00:19:33,589
(K9 WHIRRING)

284
00:19:33,673 --> 00:19:36,425
Oh, hey! Now we're in business!

285
00:19:36,550 --> 00:19:38,761
-Master?
-He recognises me!

286
00:19:38,886 --> 00:19:41,597
-Affirmative.
-Rose, give us the oil.

287
00:19:50,106 --> 00:19:53,150
I wouldn't touch it, though.
That dinner lady got all scorched.

288
00:19:53,234 --> 00:19:56,362
I'm no dinner lady.
And I don't often say that.

289
00:20:01,826 --> 00:20:04,662
Here we go. Come on, boy, here we go.

290
00:20:04,745 --> 00:20:08,040
(STUTTERING) Oil extract...

291
00:20:08,124 --> 00:20:10,042
analysing.

292
00:20:10,167 --> 00:20:13,379
-Listen to him, man! That's a voice.
-Careful. That's my dog.

293
00:20:13,462 --> 00:20:15,464
Confirmation of analysis.

294
00:20:15,548 --> 00:20:18,634
Substance is Krillitane oil.

295
00:20:18,759 --> 00:20:20,678
They're Krillitanes.

296
00:20:20,761 --> 00:20:22,471
-Is that bad?
-Very.

297
00:20:22,555 --> 00:20:26,142
Think how bad things could possibly be
and add another suitcase full of bad.

298
00:20:26,267 --> 00:20:29,061
-And what are Krillitanes?
-They're a composite race.

299
00:20:29,145 --> 00:20:32,356
Just like your culture is a mixture
of traditions from all sorts of countries,

300
00:20:32,440 --> 00:20:33,941
people you've invaded or been invaded by,

301
00:20:34,024 --> 00:20:36,485
you've got bits of Viking, bits of France,
bits of whatever.

302
00:20:36,569 --> 00:20:39,321
The Krillitanes are the same, an amalgam
of the races they've conquered.

303
00:20:39,447 --> 00:20:42,241
But they take physical aspects as well.

304
00:20:42,324 --> 00:20:45,619
They cherry-pick the best bits
from the people they destroy.

305
00:20:45,703 --> 00:20:47,079
That's why I didn't recognise them.

306
00:20:47,163 --> 00:20:49,039
The last time I saw Krillitanes
they looked just like us,

307
00:20:49,165 --> 00:20:50,916
except they had really long necks.

308
00:20:51,000 --> 00:20:53,419
What are they doing here?

309
00:20:53,502 --> 00:20:55,838
It's the children.

310
00:20:55,921 --> 00:20:58,674
They're doing something to the children.

311
00:21:06,348 --> 00:21:08,934
So, what's the deal with the tin dog?

312
00:21:09,018 --> 00:21:11,604
The Doctor likes travelling
with an entourage.

313
00:21:11,687 --> 00:21:14,523
Sometimes they're humans,
sometimes they're aliens,

314
00:21:14,607 --> 00:21:16,942
and sometimes they're tin dogs.

315
00:21:17,026 --> 00:21:19,278
What about you?
Where do you fit in the picture?

316
00:21:19,403 --> 00:21:23,199
Me? I'm their man in Havana,
I'm their technical support, I'm...

317
00:21:25,951 --> 00:21:28,621
Oh, my God. I'm the tin dog.

318
00:21:33,709 --> 00:21:35,211
On my command.

319
00:21:36,212 --> 00:21:38,589
ROSE: How many of us have there been
travelling with you?

320
00:21:38,714 --> 00:21:40,132
-Does it matter?
-Yeah, it does,

321
00:21:40,216 --> 00:21:42,510
if I'm just the latest in a long line.

322
00:21:42,593 --> 00:21:44,386
As opposed to what?

323
00:21:45,596 --> 00:21:48,224
I thought you and me were...

324
00:21:48,307 --> 00:21:49,934
I obviously got it wrong.

325
00:21:50,059 --> 00:21:53,354
I've been to the year 5 billion, right,
but this...

326
00:21:53,437 --> 00:21:56,899
Now, this is really seeing the future.
You just leave us behind.

327
00:21:58,108 --> 00:22:01,028
-Is that what you're gonna do to me?
-No. Not to you.

328
00:22:01,111 --> 00:22:03,739
But Sarah Jane.
You were that close to her once,

329
00:22:03,864 --> 00:22:07,660
and now, you never even mention her.

330
00:22:08,494 --> 00:22:10,788
-Why not?
-I don't age.

331
00:22:11,413 --> 00:22:12,957
I regenerate.

332
00:22:14,625 --> 00:22:18,963
But humans decay. You wither and you die.

333
00:22:19,296 --> 00:22:22,508
Imagine watching that happen
to someone that you...

334
00:22:22,591 --> 00:22:24,260
What, Doctor?

335
00:22:26,303 --> 00:22:29,306
You can spend
the rest of your life with me...

336
00:22:31,392 --> 00:22:34,186
but I can't spend the rest of mine with you.

337
00:22:34,311 --> 00:22:37,439
I have to live on. Alone.

338
00:22:40,442 --> 00:22:42,194
That's the curse of the Time Lords.

339
00:22:42,987 --> 00:22:44,446
Time Lord.

340
00:22:45,948 --> 00:22:47,616
(SCREECHING)

341
00:22:54,582 --> 00:22:57,001
Was that a Krillitane?

342
00:22:57,126 --> 00:23:00,963
It didn't even touch you, it just flew off.
What did it do that for?

343
00:23:06,635 --> 00:23:09,013
(SCHOOL BELL RINGING)

344
00:23:19,106 --> 00:23:22,109
Rose and Sarah, you go to the maths room.
Crack open those computers.

345
00:23:22,192 --> 00:23:24,653
I need to see the hardware inside.
Here, you might need this.

346
00:23:24,737 --> 00:23:27,031
Mickey, surveillance. I want you outside.

347
00:23:27,156 --> 00:23:28,449
Just stand outside?

348
00:23:28,532 --> 00:23:30,951
Here, take these.
You can keep K9 company.

349
00:23:31,035 --> 00:23:32,620
Don't forget to leave
the window open a crack.

350
00:23:32,703 --> 00:23:34,914
-He's metal.
-I didn't mean for him.

351
00:23:34,997 --> 00:23:38,334
-What are you gonna do?
-It's time I had a word with Mr Finch.

352
00:24:03,609 --> 00:24:07,363
-Who are you?
-My name is Brother Lassar. And you?

353
00:24:07,488 --> 00:24:09,281
The Doctor.

354
00:24:09,365 --> 00:24:11,617
Since when did Krillitanes have wings?

355
00:24:11,700 --> 00:24:14,870
It's been our form
for nearly 10 generations now.

356
00:24:14,954 --> 00:24:17,414
Our ancestors invaded Bessan.

357
00:24:17,539 --> 00:24:20,125
The people there
had some rather lovely wings.

358
00:24:20,250 --> 00:24:23,545
They made a million widows in one day,
just imagine.

359
00:24:23,671 --> 00:24:25,130
And now your shape's human.

360
00:24:25,214 --> 00:24:27,049
A personal favourite, that's all.

361
00:24:27,132 --> 00:24:30,636
-And the others?
-My brothers remain bat form.

362
00:24:30,761 --> 00:24:32,972
What you see is a simple morphic illusion.

363
00:24:33,055 --> 00:24:36,517
Scratch the surface
and the true Krillitane lies beneath.

364
00:24:36,976 --> 00:24:39,228
And what of the Time Lords?

365
00:24:39,353 --> 00:24:41,939
I always thought of you
as such a pompous race.

366
00:24:42,022 --> 00:24:44,441
Ancient, dusty senators.

367
00:24:44,525 --> 00:24:48,529
So frightened of change, and chaos.

368
00:24:49,405 --> 00:24:52,616
And, of course, they're all but extinct.

369
00:24:52,700 --> 00:24:55,536
Only you. The last.

370
00:24:55,619 --> 00:24:58,247
This plan of yours, what is it?

371
00:24:58,664 --> 00:25:01,208
-You don't know?
-That's why I'm asking.

372
00:25:01,291 --> 00:25:04,169
Well, show me how clever you are.
Work it out.

373
00:25:04,253 --> 00:25:07,673
If I don't like it, then it will stop.

374
00:25:07,756 --> 00:25:09,508
Fascinating.

375
00:25:10,342 --> 00:25:13,804
Your people were peaceful
to the point of indolence.

376
00:25:14,972 --> 00:25:17,391
You seem to be something new.

377
00:25:18,308 --> 00:25:21,103
Would you declare war on us, Doctor?

378
00:25:21,186 --> 00:25:23,564
I'm so old now.

379
00:25:25,107 --> 00:25:27,776
I used to have so much mercy.

380
00:25:30,112 --> 00:25:34,283
You get one warning. That was it.

381
00:25:34,408 --> 00:25:39,538
But we're not even enemies.
Soon, you will embrace us.

382
00:25:39,621 --> 00:25:44,084
The next time we meet,
you will join with me.

383
00:25:45,461 --> 00:25:47,296
I promise you.

384
00:25:52,426 --> 00:25:56,180
Surveillance!
You ask me, it's just another way of saying,

385
00:25:56,263 --> 00:26:00,476
"Go sit at the back of the class
with the safety scissors and glitter."

386
00:26:01,894 --> 00:26:03,312
(SIGHING)

387
00:26:04,021 --> 00:26:06,774
That'll be me talking to a metal dog, then.

388
00:26:07,649 --> 00:26:09,026
Oh!

389
00:26:10,778 --> 00:26:13,447
-It's not working.
-Give it to me.

390
00:26:14,907 --> 00:26:16,742
Used to work first time in my day.

391
00:26:16,825 --> 00:26:19,453
Well, things were a lot simpler back then.

392
00:26:19,536 --> 00:26:22,998
-Rose, can I give you a bit of advice?
-I've got a feeling you're about to.

393
00:26:23,082 --> 00:26:25,751
I know how intense
a relationship with the Doctor can be

394
00:26:25,834 --> 00:26:27,711
and I don't want you to feel I'm intruding...

395
00:26:27,795 --> 00:26:29,838
I don't feel threatened by you
if that's what you mean.

396
00:26:29,963 --> 00:26:33,592
Right. Good. Because I'm not interested
in picking up where we left off.

397
00:26:33,675 --> 00:26:34,760
No?

398
00:26:34,843 --> 00:26:38,222
With the big sad eyes and the robot dog,
what else were you doing last night?

399
00:26:38,347 --> 00:26:42,101
I was just saying how hard it was
adjusting to life back on Earth.

400
00:26:42,184 --> 00:26:46,188
The thing is, when you two met,
they'd only just got rid of rationing.

401
00:26:46,313 --> 00:26:49,191
No wonder all that space stuff
was a bit too much for you.

402
00:26:49,316 --> 00:26:52,736
I had no problem with space stuff.
I saw things you wouldn't believe.

403
00:26:52,861 --> 00:26:53,862
Try me.

404
00:26:53,946 --> 00:26:55,405
-Mummies.
-I've met ghosts.

405
00:26:55,489 --> 00:26:58,617
-Robots. Lots of robots.
-Slitheen, in Downing Street.

406
00:26:58,700 --> 00:27:00,410
-Daleks.
-Met the Emperor.

407
00:27:00,494 --> 00:27:02,371
-Antimatter monsters!
-Gas mask zombies!

408
00:27:02,496 --> 00:27:04,832
-Real living dinosaurs!
-Real living werewolf!

409
00:27:04,915 --> 00:27:08,210
-The Loch Ness monster!
-Seriously?

410
00:27:09,044 --> 00:27:10,254
Oh!

411
00:27:14,508 --> 00:27:16,635
Listen to us.

412
00:27:16,718 --> 00:27:20,222
It's like me and my mate Shareen,
the only time we fell out was over a man.

413
00:27:20,347 --> 00:27:23,142
And we're arguing over the Doctor.

414
00:27:27,396 --> 00:27:29,565
With you, did he do that thing

415
00:27:29,648 --> 00:27:32,317
where he'd explain something
at like 90 miles per hour,

416
00:27:32,401 --> 00:27:35,904
and you'd go, "What?" and he'd look at you
like you'd just dribbled on your shirt?

417
00:27:35,988 --> 00:27:37,239
All the time.

418
00:27:38,574 --> 00:27:40,450
Does he still stroke bits of the Tardis?

419
00:27:40,534 --> 00:27:44,329
Yeah! Yeah, he does!
I'm like, "Do you two want to be alone?”

420
00:27:46,832 --> 00:27:48,417
How's it going?

421
00:27:50,210 --> 00:27:51,587
What?

422
00:27:51,670 --> 00:27:54,631
Listen, I need to find out
what's programmed inside these.

423
00:27:54,756 --> 00:27:57,092
What? Stop it.

424
00:27:59,219 --> 00:28:01,847
Brothers, we must initiate the final phase.

425
00:28:01,930 --> 00:28:04,391
Get the children inside and seal the school.

426
00:28:04,933 --> 00:28:10,105
Our time has come, my brothers.
Today we shall become gods.

427
00:28:13,775 --> 00:28:15,319
(PA SYSTEM BUZZING)

428
00:28:15,402 --> 00:28:18,363
WOMAN: (ON PA SYSTEM)
All pupils to class immediately.

429
00:28:18,447 --> 00:28:22,659
And would all members of staff
please congregate in the staff room?

430
00:28:24,786 --> 00:28:27,456
Break time's finished early!
Isn't that fantastic?

431
00:28:40,969 --> 00:28:44,389
No, no, this classroom's out of bounds.
You've all got to go to the south hall.

432
00:28:44,473 --> 00:28:46,350
Off you go, south hall!

433
00:28:47,935 --> 00:28:49,811
What is it now, Mr Finch?

434
00:28:49,937 --> 00:28:53,398
Slight change in the timetable.
We're having an early lunch.

435
00:28:58,987 --> 00:29:01,073
(SCREECHING)

436
00:29:01,323 --> 00:29:03,867
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

437
00:29:08,580 --> 00:29:09,748
I can't shift it.

438
00:29:09,831 --> 00:29:11,917
I thought the sonic screwdriver
could open anything.

439
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:15,295
Anything except a deadlock seal.
There's got to be something inside here.

440
00:29:15,379 --> 00:29:16,880
What are they teaching those kids?

441
00:29:32,020 --> 00:29:33,981
Close the school.

442
00:29:37,567 --> 00:29:38,860
(BELCHING)

443
00:30:09,266 --> 00:30:12,352
You wanted the programme. There it is.

444
00:30:18,900 --> 00:30:20,736
Some sort of code.

445
00:30:53,769 --> 00:30:54,936
No.

446
00:30:57,481 --> 00:31:00,025
No, they can't be.

447
00:31:00,108 --> 00:31:01,693
-They've taken them all.
-What?

448
00:31:01,777 --> 00:31:03,779
They've taken all the children!

449
00:31:08,450 --> 00:31:09,785
Turn...

450
00:31:11,078 --> 00:31:12,954
Come on, I need some help.

451
00:31:15,123 --> 00:31:19,127
System restarting.
All primary drives functioning.

452
00:31:19,211 --> 00:31:22,589
You're working! Okay, no time to explain,
we need to get inside the school.

453
00:31:22,672 --> 00:31:25,008
Do you have, like, I don't know,
a lock-picking device?

454
00:31:25,133 --> 00:31:26,843
We are in a car.

455
00:31:26,927 --> 00:31:30,013
-Maybe a drill attachment?
-We are in a car.

456
00:31:30,097 --> 00:31:31,515
Fat lot of good you are.

457
00:31:31,640 --> 00:31:33,558
We are in a car.

458
00:31:33,642 --> 00:31:35,644
Wait a second. We're in a car.

459
00:31:36,645 --> 00:31:38,063
Get back!

460
00:31:39,481 --> 00:31:40,899
The Skasas Paradigm.

461
00:31:40,982 --> 00:31:43,110
They're trying to crack
the Skasas Paradigm.

462
00:31:43,193 --> 00:31:44,653
The Skasas what?

463
00:31:44,736 --> 00:31:47,197
The god-maker. The universal theory.

464
00:31:47,280 --> 00:31:51,410
Crack that equation and you've got control
of the building blocks of the universe.

465
00:31:51,493 --> 00:31:54,746
Time and space and matter,
yours to control.

466
00:31:54,830 --> 00:31:56,706
What, and the kids are like
a giant computer?

467
00:31:56,832 --> 00:31:58,417
Yes.

468
00:31:58,500 --> 00:32:01,253
And their learning power
is being accelerated by the oil.

469
00:32:01,336 --> 00:32:04,089
That oil from the kitchens,
it works as a conducting agent,

470
00:32:04,172 --> 00:32:05,340
makes the kids cleverer.

471
00:32:05,465 --> 00:32:07,300
But that oil's on the chips.
I've been eating them.

472
00:32:07,384 --> 00:32:10,011
-What's 59 times 357
-2065.

473
00:32:10,095 --> 00:32:11,221
Oh, my God!

474
00:32:11,346 --> 00:32:12,889
But why use children?
Can't they use adults?

475
00:32:13,014 --> 00:32:16,601
No, it's got to be children. The god-maker
needs imagination to crack it.

476
00:32:16,685 --> 00:32:20,397
They're not just using the children's brains
to break the code,

477
00:32:20,522 --> 00:32:22,691
they're using their souls.

478
00:32:23,775 --> 00:32:25,777
Let the lesson begin.

479
00:32:26,445 --> 00:32:27,737
Think of it, Doctor.

480
00:32:27,863 --> 00:32:31,116
With the paradigm solved,
reality becomes clay in our hands.

481
00:32:31,199 --> 00:32:33,869
We can shape the universe and improve it.

482
00:32:33,952 --> 00:32:36,705
Oh, yeah, the whole of creation
with the face of Mr Finch.

483
00:32:36,788 --> 00:32:38,999
Call me old-fashioned,
I like things as they are.

484
00:32:39,082 --> 00:32:43,378
You act like such a radical and yet
all you want to do is preserve the old order.

485
00:32:43,462 --> 00:32:46,631
Think of the changes that could be made
if this power was used for good.

486
00:32:46,715 --> 00:32:49,050
-What, by someone like you?
-No.

487
00:32:49,134 --> 00:32:50,552
Someone like you.

488
00:32:51,887 --> 00:32:56,183
The paradigm gives us power,
but you could give us wisdom.

489
00:32:56,266 --> 00:32:59,936
Become a god at my side.

490
00:33:00,520 --> 00:33:04,524
Imagine what you could do.
Think of the civilisations you could save.

491
00:33:04,608 --> 00:33:08,195
Perganon, Ascinta, your own people, Doctor.

492
00:33:08,278 --> 00:33:10,155
Standing tall.

493
00:33:10,238 --> 00:33:13,909
The Time Lords...reborn.

494
00:33:14,034 --> 00:33:15,410
Doctor, don't listen to him.

495
00:33:15,494 --> 00:33:17,996
And you could be with him
throughout eternity.

496
00:33:18,079 --> 00:33:19,956
Young, fresh.

497
00:33:20,081 --> 00:33:24,669
Never wither, never age, never die.
Their lives are so fleeting.

498
00:33:24,753 --> 00:33:26,254
So many goodbyes.

499
00:33:27,214 --> 00:33:29,633
How lonely you must be, Doctor.

500
00:33:29,758 --> 00:33:31,468
Join us.

501
00:33:32,177 --> 00:33:35,180
-I could save everyone.
-Yes.

502
00:33:35,263 --> 00:33:37,307
I could stop the war.

503
00:33:40,435 --> 00:33:43,355
No. The universe has to move forward.

504
00:33:43,438 --> 00:33:47,776
Pain and loss, they define us
as much as happiness or love.

505
00:33:47,859 --> 00:33:51,071
Whether it's a world or a relationship.

506
00:33:51,154 --> 00:33:54,366
Everything has its time.
And everything ends.

507
00:34:03,291 --> 00:34:04,459
Out!

508
00:34:17,556 --> 00:34:18,848
Come on!

509
00:34:18,974 --> 00:34:21,226
(SCREECHING)

510
00:34:43,456 --> 00:34:44,874
What is going on?

511
00:35:09,482 --> 00:35:11,443
-Are they my teachers?
-Yeah. I'm sorry.

512
00:35:11,526 --> 00:35:15,697
We need the Doctor alive.
As for the others, you can feast.

513
00:35:30,420 --> 00:35:32,255
(SCREECHING)

514
00:35:32,547 --> 00:35:34,257
SARAH: K9!

515
00:35:34,382 --> 00:35:37,135
Suggest you engage
running mode, mistress.

516
00:35:37,218 --> 00:35:38,595
Come on!

517
00:35:39,804 --> 00:35:41,306
DOCTOR: K9, hold them back!

518
00:35:41,389 --> 00:35:43,224
Affirmative, master.

519
00:35:45,310 --> 00:35:47,729
Maximum defence mode!

520
00:35:47,812 --> 00:35:49,147
Come on!

521
00:35:55,403 --> 00:35:57,405
Power supply failing.

522
00:35:58,156 --> 00:36:00,659
Forget the shooty dog thing.

523
00:36:00,784 --> 00:36:04,079
Power supply failing.

524
00:36:08,708 --> 00:36:12,087
It's the oil. Krillitane life forms
can't handle the oil! That's it!

525
00:36:12,212 --> 00:36:15,590
They've changed their physiology so often,
even their own oil is toxic to them.

526
00:36:15,674 --> 00:36:17,592
-How much was there in the kitchens?
-Barrels of it.

527
00:36:17,717 --> 00:36:19,260
(SCREECHING)

528
00:36:24,933 --> 00:36:26,559
We need to get to the kitchens. Mickey...

529
00:36:26,643 --> 00:36:27,852
What now? Hold the coats?

530
00:36:27,936 --> 00:36:29,771
Get all the children unplugged
and out of the school.

531
00:36:29,896 --> 00:36:32,691
DOCTOR: Now, then, bats, bats, bats.
How do we fight bats?

532
00:36:32,774 --> 00:36:34,609
(FIRE ALARM SOUNDING)

533
00:36:37,904 --> 00:36:39,948
(SCREECHING IN PAIN)

534
00:36:50,125 --> 00:36:51,751
Get after them.

535
00:36:56,798 --> 00:36:58,007
Master.

536
00:36:58,091 --> 00:37:00,218
Come on, boy! Good boy.

537
00:37:01,469 --> 00:37:04,139
Okay, listen, everyone,
we've got to get out of here!

538
00:37:17,318 --> 00:37:21,656
They've been deadlock sealed.
Finch must have done it. I can't open them.

539
00:37:21,740 --> 00:37:24,701
The vats would not withstand
a direct hit from my laser,

540
00:37:24,784 --> 00:37:27,120
but my batteries are failing.

541
00:37:27,203 --> 00:37:30,290
Right, everyone out the back door.
K9, stay with me.

542
00:37:56,191 --> 00:37:58,151
Everyone, get out. Now!

543
00:37:58,693 --> 00:38:01,237
Come on! Move! Let's go, let's go!

544
00:38:21,090 --> 00:38:23,218
Capacity for only one shot, master.

545
00:38:23,301 --> 00:38:26,763
For maximum impact,
I must be stationed directly beside the vat.

546
00:38:26,846 --> 00:38:30,308
-But you'll be trapped inside.
-That is correct.

547
00:38:30,391 --> 00:38:34,020
-I can't let you do that.
-No alternative possible, master.

548
00:38:34,103 --> 00:38:35,897
(SCREECHING)

549
00:38:40,527 --> 00:38:43,112
-Goodbye, old friend.
-Goodbye, master.

550
00:38:44,864 --> 00:38:47,408
-You good dog.
-Affirmative.

551
00:38:59,921 --> 00:39:01,965
-Where's K9?
-We need to run.

552
00:39:02,048 --> 00:39:04,759
Where is he? What have you done?

553
00:39:05,593 --> 00:39:10,139
When we find him, eat him if you must,
but bring me his brain.

554
00:39:20,108 --> 00:39:22,569
The little dog with the nasty bite.

555
00:39:24,487 --> 00:39:26,364
Not so powerful now, are you?

556
00:39:31,536 --> 00:39:34,539
Come on guys, let's go, let's go! Come on!

557
00:39:34,622 --> 00:39:36,416
Burning!

558
00:39:40,086 --> 00:39:42,672
You bad dog.

559
00:39:42,755 --> 00:39:44,007
Affirmative.

560
00:39:49,804 --> 00:39:51,389
(CHEERING)

561
00:39:55,977 --> 00:39:57,145
Yes!

562
00:39:58,479 --> 00:40:01,566
-Did you have something to do with it?
-Yeah, I did.

563
00:40:01,649 --> 00:40:03,526
Oh, my God.

564
00:40:03,651 --> 00:40:06,195
Kenny blew up the school! It was Kenny!

565
00:40:07,113 --> 00:40:09,782
ALL: (CHANTING) Kenny! Kenny! Kenny!

566
00:40:12,827 --> 00:40:14,829
-I'm sorry.
-It's all right.

567
00:40:14,996 --> 00:40:18,166
He was just a daft metal dog.

568
00:40:18,249 --> 00:40:19,834
Fine, really.

569
00:40:42,732 --> 00:40:44,525
Cup of tea?

570
00:40:56,537 --> 00:40:59,165
-You've redecorated.
-Do you like it?

571
00:40:59,248 --> 00:41:02,627
Oh, I do. Yeah.

572
00:41:02,877 --> 00:41:07,548
I preferred it as it was, but it'll do.

573
00:41:07,632 --> 00:41:08,800
I love it.

574
00:41:08,883 --> 00:41:11,719
Hey, what's 47 times 3697

575
00:41:11,844 --> 00:41:13,054
No idea.

576
00:41:13,137 --> 00:41:16,224
-It's gone now, the oil's faded.
-But you're still clever.

577
00:41:16,307 --> 00:41:19,727
-More than a match for him.
-You and me both.

578
00:41:21,938 --> 00:41:23,564
ROSE: Doctor?

579
00:41:24,565 --> 00:41:29,362
Um, we're about to head off,
but you could come with us.

580
00:41:33,116 --> 00:41:34,701
No.

581
00:41:34,784 --> 00:41:37,078
I can't do this anymore.

582
00:41:37,870 --> 00:41:40,748
Besides, I've got
a much bigger adventure ahead.

583
00:41:40,832 --> 00:41:44,419
Time I stopped waiting for you
and found a life of my own.

584
00:41:46,421 --> 00:41:48,006
Can I come?

585
00:41:49,340 --> 00:41:52,051
Not with you, I mean, with you.

586
00:41:52,135 --> 00:41:55,680
'Cause I'm not the tin dog
and I wanna see what's out there.

587
00:41:55,763 --> 00:41:57,432
Oh, go on, Doctor.

588
00:41:57,598 --> 00:42:01,936
Sarah Jane Smith and Mickey Smith,
you need a Smith on board.

589
00:42:02,020 --> 00:42:04,022
Okay, then. I could do with a laugh.

590
00:42:06,024 --> 00:42:08,568
-Rose, is that okay?
-No, great.

591
00:42:08,943 --> 00:42:10,528
Why not?

592
00:42:13,281 --> 00:42:14,782
Well, I better go.

593
00:42:19,954 --> 00:42:21,581
What do I do?

594
00:42:22,665 --> 00:42:25,251
-Do I stay with him?
-Yes.

595
00:42:25,334 --> 00:42:29,338
Some things are worth
getting your heart broken for.

596
00:42:37,847 --> 00:42:42,685
Find me, if you need to one day. Find me.

597
00:42:53,821 --> 00:42:55,114
It's daft,

598
00:42:55,198 --> 00:42:59,035
but I haven't ever thanked you
for that time and like I said,

599
00:42:59,118 --> 00:43:01,704
I wouldn't have missed it for the world.

600
00:43:01,788 --> 00:43:03,539
Something to tell the grandkids.

601
00:43:03,664 --> 00:43:07,251
Oh, I think it'll be
someone else's grandkids now.

602
00:43:07,335 --> 00:43:11,089
Right, yes, sorry.
I didn't get a chance to ask...

603
00:43:12,298 --> 00:43:15,009
There hasn't been anyone... You know.

604
00:43:15,134 --> 00:43:20,515
Well, there was this one guy.
I travelled with him for a while,

605
00:43:20,598 --> 00:43:23,768
but he was a tough act to follow.

606
00:43:25,311 --> 00:43:26,479
Goodbye, Doctor.

607
00:43:26,562 --> 00:43:30,149
-Oh, it's not goodbye.
-You say it, please. This time.

608
00:43:30,233 --> 00:43:31,526
Say it.

609
00:43:32,777 --> 00:43:34,028
Goodbye.

610
00:43:34,862 --> 00:43:36,656
My Sarah Jane.

611
00:43:55,550 --> 00:43:57,969
(WHOOSHING)

612
00:44:10,231 --> 00:44:11,399
KO!

613
00:44:12,650 --> 00:44:15,319
-Mistress.
-But you were blown up.

614
00:44:15,403 --> 00:44:16,779
The master rebuilt me.

615
00:44:16,904 --> 00:44:21,033
My systems are much improved
with new Omni-flexible hyperlink facilities.

616
00:44:21,117 --> 00:44:22,952
He replaced you with a brand-new model.

617
00:44:23,035 --> 00:44:24,078
Affirmative.

618
00:44:24,203 --> 00:44:27,290
Yeah. He does that.

619
00:44:28,207 --> 00:44:31,252
Come on, you. Home. We've got work to do.

620
00:44:31,335 --> 00:44:32,670
Affirmative.

621
00:44:42,305 --> 00:44:43,848
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

622
00:44:43,931 --> 00:44:47,435
We are under attack.
There are creatures. We can't stop them.

623
00:44:47,602 --> 00:44:50,646
I need to find out what they're looking for.
There's only one way I can do that.

624
00:44:50,730 --> 00:44:52,231
You are inside my mind.

625
00:44:52,315 --> 00:44:57,069
A spaceship from the 51st century
stalking a woman from the 18th.

626
00:44:57,153 --> 00:44:58,905
One of them must have found
the right time window.

627
00:44:58,988 --> 00:45:00,239
Now it's time to send in the troops.

628
00:45:00,323 --> 00:45:01,574
Mickey!

629
00:45:06,871 --> 00:45:10,625
The clock on the mantel is broken.
It is time!

630
00:45:10,750 --> 00:45:13,002
Doctor! Doctor!

